Fascinating mosque on its surface, just for the history, but look deeper and it's even more interesting. It is considered a masterpiece of Islamic architecture, but lacks the adornments common in later buildings. The 'uncountable' columns that hold up the vaulted ceilings are clearly reused Roman/Byzantine columns with a wild assortment of capitals and materials. Each one is a bit different in height, so they made up the difference with bricks before building the brick vaulted ceilings. There is carved Latin text (some upside-down) on the courtyard side of the minaret that clearly demonstrates the reuse of older material.

The whole courtyard is a rainwater collection system, and there are circular wells on the north end of the courtyard where you can peek down into the massive cisterns built underneath.

The little staircase in the middle of the courtyard leads to a sundial, which is also worth a look.

Worth at least half an hour to look around - more if you're really into Roman columns.

The ruins of Carthage are generally a disappointment, even if you're a Roman history buff. For the most part, they're in poor condition and poorly curated/explained. El Jem's Amphitheater and museum more than make up for the disappointment of Carthage, and it is well worth a special trip to see them.

The amphitheater is huge (3rd largest in the world), and at least has a little interpretation. You can climb all the way up to the highest levels and look down on the floor (and the town), and also explore the underground levels.

Honestly, it's better than the Roman Colosseum in many ways. Beautiful photography opportunities abound.

A 15 minute walk takes you to the museum, which is chock full of huge (room-sized) intact Roman mosaics. One of the best collections I've ever seen.

Worth at least an hour, two plus if you include the museum. A half day in El Jem is not out of order.

Beautiful mountains, but notoriously dangerous. The heat is often extreme, the trails are exposed and exhausting (people forget theyâre at elevation when theyâre hot!), and the brush is deceptively thick, making it easy to get lost and take a step off a cliff. A truly alarming number of hikers have died here, and their remains often go unfound in the dense scrub and many tiny canyons.

Also the site of the folkloric lost Dutchmanâs gold (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lost_Dutchman%27s_Gold_Mine), one of the more interesting and culturally important buried treasure stories of the West. In some versions, itâs a small but very rich gold seam; in others, itâs a cache of conquistador-looted gold hidden in a rock cleft by Apaches; presumably some people think itâs aliens. Over the last century or more, large numbers of treasure hunters have, unsurprisingly, died while offtrail in this exceptionally dangerous landscape. This has only fed the legends of curses and increased the perceived value of the gold. There are entire (fairly entertaining) books just about the histories of the various expeditions.

Strait of Juan de Fuca boundary dispute

Despite warm relations, the US and Canada manage to dispute areas at both ends of both their borders. (See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_areas_disputed_by_Canada_and_the_United_States.) This is the smallest and probably least important: the countries disagree on how to draw the median line in two areas of the Exclusive Economic Zones outside the mouth of the Strait. In short, Canada includes its inland waters as contributing to the median line, while the US uses the low tide line. (See https://www.durham.ac.uk/media/durham-university/research-/research-centres/ibru-centre-for-borders-research/maps-and-databases/publications-database/boundary-amp-security-bulletins/bsb5-3_gray.pdf for a little more detail.) The total area in dispute is slightly over 50 kmÂ² and (so far as I know) has never led to any actual incidents.
